why do we add this newline in an unrelated file?
because I was running ethernet changes at the same time.  Fixed.

you moved 3 functions to FilesystemLogWatcher, which is a great patch for trivial +2 and merge.

There is no need to combine the simple movement of these functions with other refactoring, right? It can be 2 separate patches.

which refactoring are you referring to?  everything in this patch was required to make the class raii.  the functions couldn’t be moved in a single patch, because they relied on variables that were previously in event service manager, and changing them to global variables (which they weren’t before and is arguably a refactor) just to change them back to class variables didn’t really make sense to me.

extracting function ```sendEventsToSubs``` is another refactoring
which is different from moving the functions or 
creating the RAII class.

So that is already something that can be separate. 
I don't have anything against this patch, it might well be correct.

It's just not something i can be 99% confident about.

If you split it up more, some patches will be trivial and not need testing.

Just my opinion, you are the maintainer and not need my approval to merge anything
that you determine is correct.
I don’t need your approval, but I appreciate and will incorporate the feedback.  you’re right. that method could by put in its own patch which I can do.
Broke out that method into https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/76121
Acknowledged

since this is std::optional, do we have to .emplace() it anywhere?
I only see the 
```
 filesystemLogMonitor.reset();
```
on line 278.
Yeah, it got pushed into https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/74180 because there were multiple conflicts.  I can push it here.  Fixed
Got hit in a rebase conflict when I broke out one of the changes you asked to be broken out.  You're right, obviously looks wrong here.
fixed.
